# WordPress Third-Party Integrations

This rule applies to: `*.php` files in WordPress projects that integrate with external services.

## API Authentication
- Store API credentials securely
- Use WordPress options API with encryption when appropriate
- Implement API key rotation capabilities
- Never hardcode API keys or secret tokens

## Dependency Management
- Use WordPress HTTP API for external requests
- Implement proper fallbacks for failed API calls
- Handle rate limiting and quotas gracefully
- Cache API responses when appropriate

## Error Handling
- Implement comprehensive error handling for API calls
- Provide user-friendly error messages
- Log detailed errors for debugging
- Handle timeout and connection failures

## Data Synchronization
- Design efficient synchronization strategies
- Implement webhooks when available
- Use WordPress cron for scheduled synchronization
- Provide manual sync capabilities for admins

## User Experience
- Provide clear setup and configuration interfaces
- Implement connection status indicators
- Create user-friendly settings pages
- Show progress for long-running operations

## Performance
- Minimize API calls
- Use background processing for intensive operations
- Implement caching for API responses
- Consider using transients for temporary data storage

## Security
- Validate and sanitize all data from external sources
- Implement proper capability checks for admin functions
- Apply rate limiting for outgoing requests
- Follow OAuth best practices when applicable

## Testing
- Create test environments for integrations
- Use mock responses for API testing
- Implement integration tests
- Provide sandbox mode for testing

## Documentation
- Document API usage and limitations
- Provide clear setup instructions
- Include troubleshooting guides
- Document required API permissions

## Compliance
- Respect third-party terms of service
- Handle user data according to privacy policies
- Implement proper disclosure of data sharing
- Follow GDPR and other relevant regulations
